to the editor the article medical students get taste of real life doctoring oct 23 certainly drove home the need to teach medical students the future realities of clinical practice using standardized patients ie actors to simulate medical encounters is a viable way to get feedback about how the student is doing but this should start long before the fourth and final year of medical school i have been using patient simulations for 15 years at both columbia university college of physicians and surgeons and its school of dental and oral surgery but in the students first and second years of study way before they know too much about the medical side of doctoring this is the time to concentrate on those psychological social and emotional dimensions of clinical practice before their knowledge of diagnosis and treatment add to the multidimensional patient care complexities of medical and dental practice the term standardized patients is in itself a misnomer perhaps customized would be more appropriate dr lynn m tepper hastings on hudson ny

